# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-hudi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] The open-source project to build Apache Parquet began as a joint effort between Twitter and Cloudera using the record shredding and assembly algorithm as described in Google's Dremel.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Parquet was designed as an improvement on the Trevni columnar storage format created by Doug Cutting, the creator of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] 'small compartment') refers to a style of decorative flooring and was chosen to "evoke the bottom layer of a database with an interesting layout".
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] The first version, Apache Parquet 1.0, was released in July 2013.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Since April 27, 2015, Apache Parquet has been a top-level Apache Software Foundation (ASF)-sponsored project.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the record-shredding and assembly algorithm, which accommodates the complex data structures that can be used to store data.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the Apache Thrift framework, which increases its flexibility; it can work with a number of programming languages like C++, Java, Python, PHP, etc.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] As of August 2015, Parquet supports the big-data-processing frameworks including Apache Hive, Apache Drill, Apache Impala, Apache Crunch, Apache Pig, Cascading, Presto and Apache Spark.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] It is one of the external data formats used by the pandas Python data manipulation and analysis library.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] In Parquet, compression is performed column by column, which enables different encoding schemes to be used for text and integer data.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] This strategy also keeps the door open for newer and better encoding schemes to be implemented as they are invented.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Parquet supports various compression formats: snappy, gzip, LZO, brotli, zstd, and LZ4.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Parquet has an automatic dictionary encoding enabled dynamically for data with a *small* number of unique values (i.e. below 105) that enables significant compression and boosts processing speed.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Storage of integers is usually done with dedicated 32 or 64 bits per integer.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] For small integers, packing multiple integers into the same space makes storage more efficient.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] To optimize storage of multiple occurrences of the same value, run-length encoding is used, which is where a single value is stored once along with the number of occurrences.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Parquet implements a hybrid of bit packing and RLE, in which the encoding switches based on which produces the best compression results.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] This strategy works well for certain types of integer data and combines well with dictionary encoding.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Parquet is widely used as the underlying file format in modern cloud-based data lake architectures.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Cloud storage systems such as Amazon S3, Azure Data Lake Storage, and Google Cloud Storage commonly store data in Parquet format due to its efficient columnar representation and retrieval capabilities.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Data lakehouse frameworks—including Apache Iceberg, Delta Lake, and Apache Hudi —build an additional metadata layer on top of Parquet files to support features such as schema evolution, time-travel queries, and ACID-compliant transactions.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] In these architectures, Parquet files serve as the immutable storage layer while the table formats manage data versioning and transactional integrity.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is comparable to RCFile and Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file formats — all three fall under the category of columnar data storage within the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] They all have better compression and encoding with improved read performance at the cost of slower writes.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] In addition to these features, Apache Parquet supports limited schema evolution, i.e., the schema can be modified according to the changes in the data.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] It also provides the ability to add new columns and merge schemas that do not conflict.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] Apache Arrow is designed as an in-memory complement to on-disk columnar formats like Parquet and ORC.
[src:apache-hudi/apache-parquet] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing between the two formats.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] In databases, **change data capture** (**CDC**) is a set of software design patterns used to determine and track the data that has changed (the "deltas") so that action can be taken using the changed data.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The result is a **delta-driven dataset**.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] CDC is an approach to data integration that is based on the identification, capture and delivery of the changes made to enterprise data sources.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] For instance it can be used for incremental update of data loading.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] CDC occurs often in data warehouse environments since capturing and preserving the state of data across time is one of the core functions of a data warehouse, but CDC can be utilized in any database or data repository system.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] System developers can set up CDC mechanisms in a number of ways and in any one or a combination of system layers from application logic down to physical storage.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] In a simplified CDC context, one computer system has data believed to have changed from a previous point in time, and a second computer system needs to take action based on that changed data.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The former is the source, the latter is the target.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] It is possible that the source and target are the same system physically, but that would not change the design pattern logically.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Multiple CDC solutions can exist in a single system.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Tables whose changes must be captured may have a column that represents the time of **last** change.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Names such as LAST_UPDATE, LAST_MODIFIED, etc. are common.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Any row in any table that has a timestamp in that column that is more recent than the last time data was captured is considered to have changed.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Timestamps on rows are also frequently used for optimistic locking so this column is often available.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Database designers give tables whose changes must be captured a column that contains a version number.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Names such as VERSION_NUMBER, etc. are common.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] One technique is to mark each changed row with a version number.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] A current version is maintained for the table, or possibly a group of tables.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This is stored in a supporting construct such as a reference table.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] When a change capture occurs, all data with the latest version number is considered to have changed.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Once the change capture is complete, the reference table is updated with a new version number.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] (Do not confuse this technique with row-level versioning used for optimistic locking.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] For optimistic locking each row has an independent version number, typically a sequential counter.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This allows a process to atomically update a row and increment its counter only if another process has not incremented the counter.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] But CDC cannot use row-level versions to find all changes unless it knows the original "starting" version of every row.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This technique can either supplement or complement timestamps and versioning.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] It can configure an alternative if, for example, a status column is set up on a table row indicating that the row has changed (e.g., a boolean column that, when set to true, indicates that the row has changed).
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Otherwise, it can act as a complement to the previous methods, indicating that a row, despite having a new version number or a later date, still shouldn't be updated on the target (for example, the data may require human validation).
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This approach combines the three previously discussed methods.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] As noted, it is not uncommon to see multiple CDC solutions at work in a single system, however, the combination of time, version, and status provides a particularly powerful mechanism and programmers should utilize them as a trio where possible.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The three elements are not redundant or superfluous.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] May include a publish/subscribe pattern to communicate the changed data to multiple targets.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] In this approach, triggers log events that happen to the transactional table into another queue table that can later be "played back".
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] For example, imagine an Accounts table, when transactions are taken against this table, triggers would fire that would then store a history of the event or even the deltas into a separate queue table.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The queue table might have schema with the following fields: Id, TableName, RowId, Timestamp, Operation.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The data inserted for our Account sample might be: 1, Accounts, 76, 2008-11-02 00:15, Update.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] More complicated designs might log the actual data that changed.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This queue table could then be "played back" to replicate the data from the source system to a target.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Data capture offers a challenge in that the structure, contents and use of a transaction log is specific to a database management system.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Unlike data access, no standard exists for transaction logs.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Most database management systems do not document the internal format of their transaction logs, although some provide programmatic interfaces to their transaction logs (for example: Oracle, DB2, SQL/MP, SQL/MX and SQL Server 2008).
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] As often occurs in complex domains, the final solution to a CDC problem may have to balance many competing concerns.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Change data capture both increases in complexity and reduces in value if the source system saves metadata changes when the data itself is not modified.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] For example, some Data models track the user who last looked at but did not change the data in the same structure as the data.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] This results in noise in the Change Data Capture.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Actually tracking the changes depends on the data source.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] If the data is being persisted in a modern database then Change Data Capture is a simple matter of permissions.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] If the data is not in a modern database, CDC becomes a programming challenge.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] Sometimes the slowly changing dimension is used as an alternative method.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] CDC and SCD are similar in that both methods can detect changes in a data set.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] The most common forms of SCD are type 1 (overwrite), type 2 (maintain history) or 3 (only previous and current value).
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] SCD 2 can be useful if history is needed in the target system.
[src:apache-hudi/change-data-capture] CDC overwrites in the target system (akin to SCD1), and is ideal when only the changed data needs to arrive at the target, i.e. a *delta-driven dataset*.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-hudi/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:apache-hudi/data-lakehouse] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Without concurrency control, if someone is reading from a database at the same time as someone else is writing to it, it is possible that the reader will see a half-written or inconsistent piece of data.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] For instance, when making a wire transfer between two bank accounts if a reader reads the balance at the bank when the money has been withdrawn from the original account and before it was deposited in the destination account, it would seem that money has disappeared from the bank.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Isolation is the property that provides guarantees in the concurrent accesses to data.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Isolation is implemented by means of a concurrency control protocol.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The simplest way is to make all readers wait until the writer is done, which is known as a read-write lock.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Locks are known to create contention especially between long read transactions and update transactions.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC aims at solving the problem by keeping multiple copies of each data item.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] In this way, each user connected to the database sees a *snapshot* of the database at a particular instant in time.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] When an MVCC database needs to update a piece of data, it will not overwrite the original data item with new data, but instead creates a newer version of the data item.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Thus there are multiple versions stored.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The version that each transaction sees depends on the isolation level implemented.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The most common isolation level implemented with MVCC is snapshot isolation.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] With snapshot isolation, a transaction observes a state of the data as of when the transaction started.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC provides point-in-time consistent views.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Read transactions under MVCC typically use a timestamp or transaction ID to determine what state of the DB to read, and read these versions of the data.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Read and write transactions are thus isolated from each other without any need for locking.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] However, despite locks being unnecessary, they are used by some MVCC databases such as Oracle.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Writes create a newer version, while concurrent reads access an older version.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC introduces the challenge of how to remove versions that become obsolete and will never be read.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] In some cases, a process to periodically sweep through and delete the obsolete versions is implemented.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] This is often a stop-the-world process that traverses a whole table and rewrites it with the last version of each data item.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] PostgreSQL can use this approach with its VACUUM FREEZE process.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Other databases split the storage blocks into two parts: the data part and an undo log.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The data part always keeps the last committed version.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The undo log enables the recreation of older versions of data.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The main inherent limitation of this latter approach is that when there are update-intensive workloads, the undo log part runs out of space and then transactions are aborted as they cannot be given their snapshot.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] For a document-oriented database it also allows the system to optimize documents by writing entire documents onto contiguous sections of disk—when updated, the entire document can be re-written rather than bits and pieces cut out or maintained in a linked, non-contiguous database structure.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC uses timestamps (**TS**), and *incrementing transaction IDs*, to achieve *transactional consistency*.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC ensures a transaction (**T**) never has to wait to *Read* a database object (**P**) by maintaining several versions of the object.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Each version of object **P** has both a *Read Timestamp* (**RTS**) and a *Write Timestamp* (**WTS**) which lets a particular transaction **Ti** read the most recent version of the object which precedes the transaction's *Read Timestamp* **RTS**(**Ti**).
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] A *Write* cannot complete if there are other outstanding transactions with an earlier Read Timestamp (**RTS**) to the same object.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Like people standing in line at a store, they cannot complete their checkout transaction until those in front complete theirs.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] (This is because a later transaction already depends on the old value.) Otherwise, **Ti** creates a new version of object **P** and sets the read/write timestamp **TS** of the new version to the timestamp of the transaction **TS** ← **TS**(**Ti**).
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The drawback to this system is the cost of storing multiple versions of objects in the database.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] On the other hand, reads are never blocked, which can be important for workloads mostly involving reading values from the database.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC is particularly adept at implementing true snapshot isolation, something which other methods of concurrency control frequently do either incompletely or with high performance costs.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] A structure to hold a record (row) for a database using MVCC could look like this in Rust.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The MVCC transaction identifier for insert.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The MVCC transaction identifier for delete.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] T0 wrote Object 1="Foo" and Object 2="Bar".
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] After that T1 wrote Object 1="Hello" leaving Object 2 at its original value.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The new value of Object 1 will supersede the value at 0 for all transactions that start after T1 commits at which point version 0 of Object 1 can be garbage collected.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] There is a new version as of time 2 of Object 2 which is marked as deleted and a new Object 3.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Since T2 and T3 run concurrently T2 sees the version of the database before 2 i.e. before T3 committed writes, as such T2 reads Object 2="Bar" and Object 1="Hello".
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] This is how multiversion concurrency control allows snapshot isolation reads without any locks.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Multiversion concurrency control is described in some detail in the 1981 paper "Concurrency Control in Distributed Database Systems" by Phil Bernstein and Nathan Goodman, then employed by the Computer Corporation of America.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Bernstein and Goodman's paper cites a 1978 dissertation by David P.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Reed which quite clearly describes MVCC and claims it as an original work.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] The first shipping, commercial database software product featuring MVCC was VAX Rdb/ELN, released in 1984, and created at Digital Equipment Corporation by Jim Starkey.
[src:apache-hudi/multiversion-concurrency-control] Starkey went on to create the second commercially successful MVCC database - InterBase.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] This overview will provide a high level summary of what Apache Hudi is and will orient you on how to learn more to get started.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Apache Hudi (pronounced "hoodie") pioneered the concept of "transactional data lakes", which is more popularly known today as the data lakehouse architecture.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Today, Hudi has grown into an open data lakehouse platform, with a open table format purpose-built for high performance writes on incremental data pipelines and fast query performance due to comprehensive table optimizations.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Hudi brings core database functionality directly to a data lake - tables, transactions, efficient upserts/deletes, advanced indexes, ingestion services, data clustering/compaction optimizations, and concurrency control all while keeping your data in open file formats.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Not only is Apache Hudi great for streaming workloads, but it also allows you to create efficient incremental batch pipelines.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Apache Hudi can easily be used on any cloud storage platform.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Hudi’s advanced performance optimizations, make analytical queries/pipelines faster with any of the popular query engines including, Apache Spark, Flink, Presto, Trino, Hive, etc.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Read the docs for more use case descriptions and check out who's using Hudi, to see how some of the largest data lakes in the world including Uber, Amazon, ByteDance, Robinhood and more are transforming their production data lakes with Hudi.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Hudi-rs is the native Rust implementation for Apache Hudi, which also provides bindings to Python.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] It expands the use of Apache Hudi for a diverse range of use cases in the non-JVM ecosystems.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] See more in the "Design & Concepts" section of the docs.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Take a look at recent blog posts that go in depth on certain topics or use cases.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Sometimes the fastest way to learn is by doing.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Apache Hudi is community-focused and community-led and welcomes new-comers with open arms.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Leverage the following resources to learn more, engage, and get help as you get started.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] See all the ways to engage with the community here.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Attend monthly community calls to learn best practices and see what others are building.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Apache Hudi welcomes you to join in on the fun and make a lasting impact on the industry as a whole.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] See our contributor guide to learn more, and don’t hesitate to directly reach out to any of the current committers to learn more.
[src:apache-hudi/overview] Have an idea, an ask, or feedback about a pain-point, but don’t have time to contribute?
